---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'reading-the-figure')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    The separate techniques (houses, Witnesses, perfection, aspects, company, points) must finally
    be brought together into one answer. The masters give a settled order for this: which finding
    decides the matter, which findings only qualify it, and which question each finding is allowed
    to answer.
  </p>

  <h2>Reach the answer</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Start from perfection. The perfection scan decides whether the thing reaches the asker, and a denial is itself the answer, which no later finding overturns.</li>
    <li>Read the triad for the shape of the matter: the Judge gives the end, the Witnesses the beginning and the course.</li>
    <li>Take the quality of the perfecting figures for how a yes comes about.</li>
    <li>Take strength and aspect as qualifications only. Angles are stronger than succedents, and succedents than cadents, but strength is not goodness, and aspects and dignities never reverse the scan.</li>
    <li>Add the later techniques, the way of the point, the Part of Fortune, and timing, for detail and to break ties, never as a replacement for the foundations.</li>
    <li>Give each finding its own house and its own role, and make sure every finding answers the question that was actually asked.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <p>
    Cattan reckons eight ways a figure is judged good or unfortunate; Crowley reduces the whole
    method to a checklist:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="method" />
</Prose>
